# Secrets are `op://` REFERENCES, not values: the value lives in 1Password
# (`op://DevOps/iacarus`) and config.sh resolves every reference in one
# `op inject` call when a script starts. A reference cannot reveal a secret,
# and no secret ever lands in this file. Public config stays literal, on
# purpose — a file where every line is a reference stops telling you which
# lines actually matter.
#
# On a machine without 1Password (a mon box), replace references with
# literals or leave them out; config.sh only invokes op when a reference
# is present.

# SSH KEYS
#   > ⚠ IaCarus assumes the path `~` ($HOME) to setup and clean the following:
#   - `config` file, that holds the ssh connection configuration.
#   - `known_hosts` file, that holds the trusted ssh hosts.
#   > If you have another "pattern" on your system, setup the SSH_HOME_PATH:
SSH_HOME_PATH=$HOME/.ssh

#   1. if you need to generate a new key pair:
#   `ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -f ~/.ssh/key-name -C "comment-to-identify-the-key"`
#   OR
#   `ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -f <whatever-you-set-on_SSH_HOME_PATH>/key-name -C "comment-to-identify-the-key"`
#   2. if not, you could use one of your ssh keys.
SSH_KEY_PATH=$SSH_HOME_PATH/key-name
SSH_PUBLIC_KEY_PATH=${SSH_KEY_PATH}.pub
SSH_PRIVATE_KEY_PATH=${SSH_KEY_PATH}

# HETZNER VPS
#   > These control what `make vps-new` provisions. Defaults below match
#   > the cheapest shared-vCPU tier at the time of writing - always check
#   > the Hetzner console for current server types, locations and images:
#   > https://console.hetzner.cloud
VPS_BASE_NAME="hetzner-vps-"
VPS_TYPE="cx23"
VPS_LOCATION="hel1"
VPS_IMAGE="ubuntu-24.04"
ENVIRONMENT="development"
VPS_ADMIN_USER="hzr-user"

# CLOUDFLARE
#   > For the next steps you might need to provide a valid international
#   > credit card, despite the generous free tier, the Zero Trust and R2
#   > Storage have paid features.

# CLOUDFLARE API BEARER TOKEN (APP ORCHESTRATOR TOKEN FACTORY)
#   > Used by `make vps-app-add` / `make vps-app-remove` to programmatically
#   > MINT and REVOKE per-app, bucket-scoped R2 tokens. This is a high-level
#   > token - keep it safe. The per-app child tokens it creates are locked to
#   > only that app's two buckets.
#   1. access your cloudflare account: https://dash.cloudflare.com
#   2. "Manage Account" > "Account API Tokens" > "Create Token" > custom token.
#   3. add TWO account permissions:
#      - "API Tokens"          : Edit  (to create/delete tokens)
#      - "Workers R2 Storage"  : Edit  (you can only grant R2 perms you hold)
#   4. scope "Account Resources" to your account, set TTL, and create it.
#   5. optional, but recommended, configure "Client IP Address Filtering".

#   your Cloudflare Account ID ("Overview" page > 'Account Details'). This is
#   the single, canonical account id - shared by the token factory AND the R2
#   S3 endpoint below.
CF_ACCOUNT_ID=

#   the bearer token value created in step #2 above.
CF_API_BEARER_TOKEN=op://DevOps/iacarus/cf/api_bearer_token

# CLOUDFLARE ZERO TRUST TUNNEL
#   1. access your cloudflare account: https://dash.cloudflare.com
#   2. go to "Zero Trust" (under 'PROTECT & CONNECT' menu group).
#   3. go to "Connectors" (under 'Networks' menu group).
#   4. click on "+ Create a tunnel" button.
#   5. choose "Cloudflared" by clicking on "Select Cloudflared".
#   6. give it a "Name" and click the "Save tunnel" button.
#   7. in the "Configure", under "Choose your environment" hit "Docker".
#   8. copy the docker command under "Install and run a connector".
#   9. only the token is needed, looks like: eyJhIjoiMjg3YTUyNDAyZG...

# a cloudflare tunnel to use for smoke test!
CF_TUNNEL_SMOKE_TEST_TOKEN=op://DevOps/iacarus/tunnel/smoke_test_token

# NOT consumed by any IaCarus script - no script here runs a persistent
# tunnel. Give each app its own tunnel as a Kamal accessory in that app's
# own deploy.yml + .kamal/secrets instead (see root README.md's
# CF_TUNNEL_TOKEN note). Kept here only for an ad-hoc/manual tunnel on the
# box if you want one.
CF_TUNNEL_TOKEN=op://DevOps/iacarus/tunnel/token

# CLOUDFLARE R2 STORAGE
#   1. access your cloudflare account: https://dash.cloudflare.com
#   2. go to "Overview" (under 'BUILD' > 'Storage & Databases' >
#      'R2 object storage' menu group).
#   (You might need click a "Create R2 Account"-like button).
#   3. click on "{ } Manage" buton on "API Tokens" ('Account Details' session).
#   4. click on "Create Account API token" button.
#   5. give it a "Name".
#   6. select "Admin Read & Write" under "Permissions".
#   7. leave the "TTL" as "Forever" (or select it).
#   8. optional, but recommended, configure the "Client IP Address Filtering".
#   9. hit the "Create Account API Token".

# cloudflare R2 storage token
#  10. copy the value under "Token value" label.
# NOT consumed by any IaCarus script - the S3-compatible pair below is all
# scripts here actually use. It's kept for reference: that pair is
# cryptographically derived from this same token (id -> Access Key ID,
# SHA-256(value) -> Secret Access Key), so this raw value is only needed if
# you ever call Cloudflare's native R2 API directly.
CF_R2_TOKEN=op://DevOps/iacarus/cf/r2_token

# cloudflare R2 storage tokens : S3 interface
#  11. check this value under "Use jurisdiction-specific endpoints
#      for S3 clients:" label or in the "Overview" page
#      (under 'Account Details' session). It reuses the CF_ACCOUNT_ID set at
#      the top of the CLOUDFLARE section above.
CF_R2_S3_CLIENT_URL=https://${CF_ACCOUNT_ID}.r2.cloudflarestorage.com

#  12. copy the value under "Access Key ID" label.
CF_R2_S3_CLIENT_ACCESS_KEY_ID=op://DevOps/iacarus/r2/s3_access_key_id

#  13. copy the value under "Secret Access Key" label.
CF_R2_S3_CLIENT_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=op://DevOps/iacarus/r2/s3_secret_access_key

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# MON (OBSERVABILITY) - all optional, shown with their defaults
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# App board (`make mon-apps`) verdict thresholds, on TOTAL round-trip in ms.
# NOTE these measure the trip from wherever the VIEWER runs, so they describe
# your vantage point, not the app. Reference: a laptop in Brazil hitting a
# Helsinki box behind a Cloudflare tunnel sees ~250ms steady (the app itself
# answers in 3-6ms on the box); a mon box in Europe would see ~10ms and should
# run far tighter numbers. Measure your own baseline before trusting these.
# MON_LATENCY_WARN_MS=1200
# MON_LATENCY_CRIT_MS=3000

# Seconds between redraws of the live board, and the per-request curl timeout.
# MON_REFRESH_SECONDS=10
# MON_HTTP_TIMEOUT=15

# Warn when a TLS certificate expires within this many days.
# MON_TLS_WARN_DAYS=21

# Path to the app registry. Defaults to mon/registry.json inside the repo;
# point elsewhere if a mon box keeps its registry outside the checkout.
# MON_REGISTRY=
